1 650.120. 1. There is hereby created in the state
2 treasury the "Cyber Crime Investigation Fund". The
3 treasurer shall be custodian of the fund and may approve
4 disbursements from the fund in accordance with sections
5 30.170 and 30.180. The department of public safety shall be
6 the administrator of the fund. Moneys in the fund shall be
7 used solely for the administration of the grant program
8 established under this section. Notwithstanding the
9 provisions of section 33.080 to the contrary, any moneys
10 remaining in the fund at the end of the biennium shall not
11 revert to the credit of the general revenue fund. The state
12 treasurer shall invest moneys in the fund in the same manner
13 as other funds are invested. Any interest and moneys earned
14 on such investments shall be credited to the fund.
15 2. The department of public safety shall create a
16 program to distribute grants to multijurisdictional internet
17 cyber crime law enforcement task forces, multijurisdictional
18 enforcement groups, as defined in section 650.153, that are
19 investigating internet sex crimes against children, and
20 other law enforcement agencies. The program shall be funded
21 by the cyber crime investigation fund created under
22 subsection 1 of this section. Not more than three percent
126

23 of the money in the fund may be used by the department to
24 pay the administrative costs of the grant program. The
25 grants shall be awarded and used to pay the salaries of
26 detectives and computer forensic personnel whose focus is
27 investigating internet sex crimes against children,
28 including but not limited to enticement of a child as it
29 existed prior to August 28, 2026, grooming or enticement of
30 a minor, possession or promotion of child [pornography]
31 sexual abuse material, provide funding for the training of
32 law enforcement personnel and prosecuting and circuit
33 attorneys as well as their assistant prosecuting and circuit
34 attorneys, and purchase necessary equipment, supplies, and
35 services. The funding for such training may be used to
36 cover the travel expenses of those persons participating.
37 3. A panel is hereby established in the department of
38 public safety to award grants under this program and shall
39 be comprised of the following members:
40 (1) The director of the department of public safety,
41 or his or her designee;
42 (2) Two members appointed by the director of the
43 department of public safety from a list of six nominees
44 submitted by the Missouri Police Chiefs Association;
45 (3) Two members appointed by the director of the
46 department of public safety from a list of six nominees
47 submitted by the Missouri Sheriffs' Association;
48 (4) Two members of the state highway patrol appointed
49 by the director of the department of public safety from a
50 list of six nominees submitted by the Missouri State
51 Troopers Association;
52 (5) One member of the house of representatives
53 appointed by the speaker of the house of representatives; and
54 (6) One member of the senate appointed by the
55 president pro tem.
127

56 The panel members who are appointed under subdivisions (2),
57 (3), and (4) of this subsection shall serve a four-year term
58 ending four years from the date of expiration of the term
59 for which his or her predecessor was appointed. However, a
60 person appointed to fill a vacancy prior to the expiration
61 of such a term shall be appointed for the remainder of the
62 term. Such members shall hold office for the term of his or
63 her appointment and until a successor is appointed. The
64 members of the panel shall receive no additional
65 compensation but shall be eligible for reimbursement for
66 mileage directly related to the performance of panel duties.
67 4. Local matching amounts, which may include new or
68 existing funds or in-kind resources including but not
69 limited to equipment or personnel, are required for
70 multijurisdictional internet cyber crime law enforcement
71 task forces and other law enforcement agencies to receive
72 grants awarded by the panel. Such amounts shall be
73 determined by the state appropriations process or by the
74 panel.
75 5. When awarding grants, priority should be given to
76 newly hired detectives and computer forensic personnel.
77 6. The panel shall establish minimum training
78 standards for detectives and computer forensic personnel
79 participating in the grant program established in subsection
80 2 of this section.
81 7. Multijurisdictional internet cyber crime law
82 enforcement task forces and other law enforcement agencies
83 participating in the grant program established in subsection
84 2 of this section shall share information and cooperate with
85 the highway patrol and with existing internet crimes against
86 children task force programs.
128

87 8. The panel may make recommendations to the general
88 assembly regarding the need for additional resources or
89 appropriations.
90 9. The power of arrest of any peace officer who is
91 duly authorized as a member of a multijurisdictional
92 internet cyber crime law enforcement task force shall only
93 be exercised during the time such peace officer is an active
94 member of such task force and only within the scope of the
95 investigation on which the task force is working.
96 Notwithstanding other provisions of law to the contrary,
97 such task force officer shall have the power of arrest, as
98 limited in this subsection, anywhere in the state and shall
99 provide prior notification to the chief of police of a
100 municipality or the sheriff of the county in which the
101 arrest is to take place. If exigent circumstances exist,
102 such arrest may be made and notification shall be made to
103 the chief of police or sheriff as appropriate and as soon as
104 practical. The chief of police or sheriff may elect to work
105 with the multijurisdictional internet cyber crime law
106 enforcement task force at his or her option when such task
107 force is operating within the jurisdiction of such chief of
108 police or sheriff.
